1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Nbd7 5. d3 b6 6. c4 Bb7 7. cxd5 exd5 8.
Nc3 Be7 9. e4 $1 dxe4 10. dxe4 Nc5
{ [Diagram] White has a central pawn majority and the e-pawn gives him a central space advantage. Black’s King isn’t castled yet, which gives White some options that a castled King wouldn’t offer him (for example, Black won’t want to start a fight until he gets his King to safety). Earlier I mentioned the potential hole on c6 and the nice outpost on f5. With all this information in mind, white’s next move should make perfect sense. }
11. Nd4 $1 { White instantly targets both c6 and f5. } 11... O-O
{ 11…Nfxe4? is suicide since this capture opens a road right to the uncastled black King: 12.Nxe4 Bxe4 (12…Nxe4 13.Re1) 13.Bxe4 Nxe4 14.Re1 Nf6 15.Qe2 and the game is already over. }
12. e5 $1 Bxg2
{ Perhaps Black should have considered 12…Nd5 though White would then have a few ways to a comfortable edge. The simplest: 13.Nc6 Bxc6 (13…Nxc3?? 14.Nxd8 Nxd1 15.Nxb7 wins) 14.Nxd5 when 14…Bxd5 (14…Bb5!? 15.Re1 Rc8 16.Qg4) 15.Bxd5 gives White two active Bishops in an open position. Now, after 12…Bxg2, White gains access to the c6-square. }
13. Kxg2 Nd5 14. Nc6 { A Godzilla of Knights! } 14... Nxc3 15. bxc3 Qe8 16. Qd5
Kh8 $2 17. Ba3 f5 18. f4 Rg8 19. Rad1 Bf8 20. Nd8 $1 Rxd8 21. Qxd8 Qa4 22. Bxc5
Bxc5 23. Qd2 Qe4+ 24. Rf3
{ Knights lose a lot of their pop if you can take away (or deprive them of access to) all their advanced support points. }
