g5 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. Qc2 dxc4 12. Bxc4 c5 13. Rfd1 g4 14. Ne1 cxd4 15.
exd4 Nb6 16. Be2 h5 17. Ne4 Qg6 18. Nc3 Qxc2 19. Nxc2 Bd7 20. Rd2 Bh6 21. Ne3
f5 22. g3 f4 23. gxf4 Bxf4 24. Re1 Bc6
{ [Diagram] White seems to be under heavy pressure since black’s Bishop pair appears quite fearsome and is clearly better than white’s Bishop and Knight. Ivanchuk realizes there’s nothing he can do about the guy on f4, but the monster on c6 is quite another matter. }
25. Bb5 $1
{ White makes use of our anti-Bishop pair formula. A swap of the passive Bishop on e2 for the reaper on c6 takes a lot of the heat off of white’s game. }
25... Bf3 { “No, I don’t want to trade.” } 26. Be2 { “I insist!” } 26... Bc6
