Qxg4 Nxd4 9. Qd1 e5 10. Nb5 O-O 11. Qd2 Qe7 12. O-O-O Nxb5 13. cxb5
{ , 1/2-1/2. It turns out that Wells had pondered the same thing and set out to discover what Kasparov’s improvement was (Much later we discovered that Kasparov didn’t have an improvement and entered the whole line more or less by mistake). Wells showed me a very inventive idea for Black, but for some reason he didn’t seem to have that much faith in it. On the other hand, I continued to look at it and thought the whole line was extremely interesting. Again, luck was on my side since I arrived at Kasparov’s final position a few days later in a game against E. Anka (now a grandmaster). }
